crops.presented_by: Dr. Walter Koelz, through Prof. H. H. Bartlett
crops.institution_involved: University of Michigan, Ann Arbor, Mich.
crops.description: A low herbaceous perennial, not over 3 feet high, native to northern India. The compound leaves have 5 to 9 deeply serrate, lanceolate leaflets about 2 inches long, and the rose-colored, funnel-shaped flowers about 1 inch long are borne in terminal racemes 6 to 8 inches long. Collected on sunny bare cliffs.

crops.description: Collected at about 13,000 feet altitude. A tall herbaceous perennial, found growing in masses, with lanceolate leaves 1 to 2 feet long in a basal rosette. The stem rises to about 6 feet and bears a spike 2 to 3 feet long of white flowers. Native to India. For previous introduction see 91626.

crops.presented_by: Dr. Walter Koelz, through Prof. H. H. Bartlett
crops.institution_involved: University of Michigan, Ann Arbor, Mich.
crops.description: Collected at about 11,000 feet altitude. A stout herb up to about 3 feet high, white woolly throughout, with rounded, cordate, long-stemmed leaflets 1 to 3 inches across and dense whorls of rose-colored or purple flowers. Native to northwestern India at altitudes of 7,000 to 11,000 feet.

crops.presented_by: Dr. Walter Koelz, through Prof. H. H. Bartlett
crops.institution_involved: University of Michigan, Ann Arbor, Mich.
crops.description: Native to the Himalayas between about 5,000 and 12,000 feet altitude. Bulbs grow close to the surface; hollow stems reach 6 to 9 feet; handsome cordate leaves are shining dark green above and paler beneath. The large fragrant white flowers, often up to 12 in a raceme, are slightly greenish outside, and the inner surface of the segments is tinged with deep purple. For previous introduction see 102833.

crops.presented_by: Dr. Walter Koelz, through Prof. H. H. Bartlett
crops.institution_involved: University of Michigan, Ann Arbor, Mich.
crops.description: Collected on a cold semiarid slope at about 10,000 feet altitude. A well-formed bush about 7 feet high, with transparent white fruits that are eaten by birds.

crops.presented_by: Dr. Walter Koelz, through Prof. H. H. Bartlett
crops.institution_involved: University of Michigan, Ann Arbor, Mich.
crops.description: Collected at about 10,000 feet altitude. A small, much-branched shrub with small elliptic-orbicular entire leaves, green and nearly glabrous above and more or less hairy beneath. The orange flowers are borne in pairs toward the ends of the branchlets. Native to the Himalayas and closely allied to Lonicera hypoleuca.
